    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2426471816" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2426471816" />
    <a title="Kelley" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5861649-kelley"><img alt="Kelley" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1630278978p2/5861649.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2426471816?book_show_action=true">Jun 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kelley" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kelley" href="/user/show/5861649-kelley">Kelley</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/36687064-six-days-of-the-condor">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2426471816" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8784578093403107306"><strong>An entertaining but stereotypical novel </strong><br/><br/>I enjoyed this book as an entertaining spy thriller, that was a light enough, escapist read. I knew this story as an old Robert Redford movie. And actually I was reminded of Robert Ludlum’s Jason Bourne novels (which are much better in every way actually). My single complaint was the writer used a few too many coincidental moments to opportunely move the story forward. The worst was in the end when a bad guy confessed everything out of the blue to the hero</span>
  <span id="freeText8784578093403107306" style="display:none"><strong>An entertaining but stereotypical novel </strong><br /><br />I enjoyed this book as an entertaining spy thriller, that was a light enough, escapist read. I knew this story as an old Robert Redford movie. And actually I was reminded of Robert Ludlum’s Jason Bourne novels (which are much better in every way actually). My single complaint was the writer used a few too many coincidental moments to opportunely move the story forward. The worst was in the end when a bad guy confessed everything out of the blue to the hero, tying up all the lose ends. How convenient to use this stereotypical writer’s cop out. I enjoy this genre of story and might read more in the series in the future just to see if the author grew in writing skill as the series progressed.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8784578093403107306" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


